files.Title: Priority_Queue.FastPriorityQueue<T>
files.Summary: An implementation of a min-Priority Queue using a heap. Has O(1) .Contains()! See https://github.com/BlueRaja/High-Speed-Priority-Queue-for-C-Sharp/wiki/Getting-Started for more information

files.Title: Priority_Queue.GenericPriorityQueue<TItem, TPriority>
files.Summary: A copy of StablePriorityQueue which also has generic priority-type

files.Title: Priority_Queue.IPriorityQueue<TItem, TPriority>
files.Summary: The IPriorityQueue interface. This is mainly here for purists, and in case I decide to add more implementations later. For speed purposes, it is actually recommended that you don't access the priority queue through this interface, since the JIT can (theoretically?) optimize method calls from concrete-types slightly better.

files.Title: Priority_Queue.SimplePriorityQueue<TItem>
files.Summary: A simplified priority queue implementation. Is stable, auto-resizes, and thread-safe, at the cost of being slightly slower than FastPriorityQueue This class is kept here for backwards compatibility. It's recommended you use Simple

files.Title: Priority_Queue.SimplePriorityQueue<TItem, TPriority>
files.Summary: A simplified priority queue implementation. Is stable, auto-resizes, and thread-safe, at the cost of being slightly slower than FastPriorityQueue

files.Title: Priority_Queue.StablePriorityQueue<T>
files.Summary: A copy of FastPriorityQueue which is also stable - that is, when two nodes are enqueued with the same priority, they are always dequeued in the same order. See https://github.com/BlueRaja/High-Speed-Priority-Queue-for-C-Sharp/wiki/Getting-Started for more information
